public class Fibonacci {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int first = 0, second = 1, third = 1;
        System.out.println(first);
        System.out.println(second);
        while (third <= 10) {
            third = first + second;
            first = second;
            second = third;
            System.out.println(third);
        }
    }
}

This program starts by defining three variables: first, second, and third. The first two numbers in the sequence are always 0 and 1, so the first and second variables are initialized to those values. The third variable is initialized to 1, as the third number in the sequence is always the sum of the first two numbers.

The program then enters a while loop that will continue until the third number in the sequence is greater than or equal to 10. In each iteration of the loop, the third number is calculated as the sum of the first and second numbers. The first number becomes the second number, and the second number becomes the third number. This process continues until the tenth number in the sequence is reached.

Each number in the sequence is printed with a println statement. The program ends when the while loop ends, which is when the third number in the sequence is greater than 10.

